Network analysis using DNA metabarcoding data discloses important roles and links in the seabird community of the Eastern Tropical Atlantic

1 Data preparation

For this work we will analyse the diet composition of the seabird community of Cabo Verde.

Three seabird species breed throughout the year, i.e., continuous breeders:

  • Brown booby (Sula leucogaster; SL),
  • Red-billed tropicbird (Phaethon aethereus; PA)
  • Cape Verde storm-petrel (Hydrobates jabejabe; HJ).

And three seabird species are seasonal breeders, two breeding in summer, and one in winter:

  • Cape Verde shearwater (Calonectris edwardsii; CE) - Summer
  • Bulwers petrel (Bulweria bulwerii; BB) - Summer
  • Boyds shearwaters (Puffinus lherminieri boydi; PB) - Winter

1.1 Matrices

The database was imported

data_seabirds <- read_excel("Database.xlsx", sheet = 1, na = "")

data_seabirds <- as.data.frame(data_seabirds)

Data was formatted as a matrix of samples x MOTU

sample.matrix.motu.wide <- dcast(data_seabirds, Extraction_ID ~ final_id, function(x) if(length(x)>=1) 1 else 0, value.var = "final_id")

PA.matrix.motu <- sample.matrix.motu.wide %>% remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="Extraction_ID")

The factors of each sample was extracted

factors <-data_seabirds %>% dplyr::select(Extraction_ID, host_species, Year, Guild, Site, season, host_season)

factors <- distinct(factors, Extraction_ID, .keep_all = TRUE)
factors[] <- lapply(factors[colnames(factors)], as.factor)

factors.ord <- factors[order(factors$Extraction_ID),] # to order samples
factors.ord <- factors.ord %>% remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="Extraction_ID")

factors.ord[] <- lapply(factors.ord[colnames(factors.ord)], as.factor)

Data was analysed at two scales of resolution:

  • Community scale - To explore interspecific and inter-seasonal differences
  • Seasonal scale - To assess the contribution of each seasonal populations to the trophic network

2 Data analysis - Community scale

2.1 Frequency of occurence (%)

sample.matrix.motu.long <- gather(sample.matrix.motu.wide, Species, Presence, "Acanthuridae":"Trichiuridae", factor_key=TRUE)
sample.matrix.motu.long <- merge(sample.matrix.motu.long, factors)

sample.matrix.motu.long.good <- ddply(.data = sample.matrix.motu.long, .var = c("host_species", "Species"), .fun = summarise,
    n = length(Presence),
    present = sum(Presence %in% c("1")),
    prop = present / n * 100
)

sample.matrix.motu.wide.good <- sample.matrix.motu.long.good %>%
  subset(select=c("host_species", "n", "Species", "prop"))%>%
  spread(Species, prop)
sample.matrix.motu.wide.good <- sample.matrix.motu.wide.good %>% remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="host_species")

2.1.1 Ranked Frequency of occurence (FO) plots

To build the Ranked Frequency of occurrence plots, the FO table was separated by all seabird species, to allow to rank each seabird prey by its %FO. Then, the individual matrices were merged together to build the plot.

Plot

BioR.theme <- theme(
        panel.background = element_blank(),
        panel.border = element_blank(),
        panel.grid = element_blank(),
        axis.line = element_line("gray25"),
        text = element_text(size = 16, family="Helvetica"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 14, colour = "gray25"),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 16, colour = "gray25"),
        legend.title = element_text(size = 16),
        legend.text = element_text(size = 16),
        legend.key = element_blank())


FOplot.spp <- ggplot(data=FO_plot_spp, aes(x = rank, y = prop)) + 
    xlim(0, 25) +
    ylim(0, 100) +
    geom_line(aes(colour=host_species), size=1) +
    geom_point(aes(colour=host_species), size=4, alpha=0.7) +
    geom_text_repel(data=subset(FO_plot_spp, rank < 5), 
        aes(label=Species), 
        angle=0, size = 5, nudge_x=5, nudge_y=5, show.legend=FALSE) +
    BioR.theme + facet_wrap(~ host_species)

2.2.2 Extrapolation of MOTU Diversity

Incidence matrices were built, and two lists were defined: one with seasonal breeders, other with continuous breeders, to call their curves separately.

incidence.matrix.motu.phaeton <- as.data.frame(t(PA.matrix.motu.phaeton))
incidence.matrix.motu.sula_leuco <- as.data.frame(t(PA.matrix.motu.sula_leuco))
incidence.matrix.motu.bulweria <- as.data.frame(t(PA.matrix.motu.bulweria))
incidence.matrix.motu.calonectris <- as.data.frame(t(PA.matrix.motu.calonectris))
incidence.matrix.motu.puffinus <- as.data.frame(t(PA.matrix.motu.puffinus))
incidence.matrix.motu.hydrobates <- as.data.frame(t(PA.matrix.motu.hydrobates))


list_seabirds1 = list(BB = incidence.matrix.motu.bulweria, CE = incidence.matrix.motu.calonectris, PB = incidence.matrix.motu.puffinus)

list_seabirds2 = list(PA = incidence.matrix.motu.phaeton, SL = incidence.matrix.motu.sula_leuco, HJ = incidence.matrix.motu.hydrobates)

ChaoEst <- ChaoRichness(c(list_seabirds1,list_seabirds2), datatype="incidence_raw", conf = 0.95)

2.3 Network analysis using FO%

An interaction network from the whole MOTU matrix was built using the FO% to index the strength of interactions. Then, we used several metrics to quantify several key characteristics of the network.

seabirds.net.matrix <- sample.matrix.motu.long.good[,c(1,2,5)] %>% filter(prop > 0) %>% dplyr::rename(higher = host_species, lower = Species, freq = prop)
seabirds.net.matrix$webID = "caboverde"
seabirds.net.matrix <- seabirds.net.matrix[, c(1, 2, 4, 3)]

seq.high <- as.data.frame(seabirds.net.matrix$higher)%>% dplyr::rename(seq.high = "seabirds.net.matrix$higher") %>% distinct(seq.high)
seq.low <- as.data.frame(seabirds.net.matrix$lower)%>% dplyr::rename(seq.low = "seabirds.net.matrix$lower") %>% distinct(seq.low)

seabirds.network <- frame2webs(data.frame(seabirds.net.matrix),type.out="list")

2.3.1 Species level metrics

species_indeces <- specieslevel(seabirds.network$caboverde, index=c("normalised degree", "d"))

2.4 Network analysis using FI

In this analysis, an interaction network from the whole MOTU matrix was built using the Frequency of Interaction (FI) to index the strength of interactions. Then, we used several metrics to quantify several key characteristics of the network.

seabirds.net.matrix <- sample.matrix.motu.long.good[,c(1,2,4)] %>% filter(present > 0) %>% dplyr::rename(higher = host_species, lower = Species, freq = present)
seabirds.net.matrix$webID = "caboverde"
seabirds.net.matrix <- seabirds.net.matrix[, c(1, 2, 4, 3)]

seq.high <- as.data.frame(seabirds.net.matrix$higher)%>% dplyr::rename(seq.high = "seabirds.net.matrix$higher") %>% distinct(seq.high)
seq.low <- as.data.frame(seabirds.net.matrix$lower)%>% dplyr::rename(seq.low = "seabirds.net.matrix$lower") %>% distinct(seq.low)

seabirds.network <- frame2webs(data.frame(seabirds.net.matrix),type.out="list")

quantile(nulls_zvalues_HL, 0.95)
##       95% 
## 0.7071068

Several outliers were detected, which are singletons: such MOTU only appears in one sample, and those samples only have this MOTU

The analysis continued without these outliers.

New dataframes were build, both MOTU matrix and factor matrix.

motu_outliers <- c("BUBU_18_RA_37", "BUBU_18_RA_57", "BUBU_19_IC_02", "BUBU_19_IC_03", "BUBU_19_RA_15", "BUBU_19_RA_18", "BUBU_19_RA_19", "BUBU_19_RA_25", "CAED_18_CV_03", "CAED_18_CV_07", "CAED_18_RA_16", "CAED_18_RA_21", "HYJA_19_RA_02", "HYJA_19_RA_03", "HYJA_19_RA_05", "PHAE_18_CD_02", "PHAE_18_SG_06", "PUBO_19_IC_23")

data_seabirds.no_outliers.motu <- subset(data_seabirds, !(Extraction_ID %in% motu_outliers))

PA.matrix.motu.no_outliers <- dcast(data_seabirds.no_outliers.motu, Extraction_ID ~ final_id, function(x) if(length(x)>=1) 1 else 0, value.var = "final_id")
PA.matrix.motu.no_outliers2 <- PA.matrix.motu.no_outliers %>% remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="Extraction_ID")

factors.no_outliers <- data_seabirds.no_outliers.motu %>% dplyr::select(Extraction_ID, host_species, Year, Guild, Site, season, host_season) %>% distinct(Extraction_ID, .keep_all = TRUE)
factors.no_outliers[] <- lapply(factors.no_outliers[colnames(factors.no_outliers)], as.factor)

factors.no_outliers.ord <- factors.no_outliers[order(factors.no_outliers$Extraction_ID),] %>% remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="Extraction_ID")

mvabund.seabirds.motu <- merge(PA.matrix.motu.no_outliers, factors.no_outliers)

3 Data analysis - Seasonal scale

Populations with smaller sample size than 10 were discarded to avoid poor frequency of occurrence estimates, and therefore HJ samples were not considered for this analysis.

This resulted on a total of 4 summer populations (CE, BB, SL(S), PA(S)) and 3 winter populations (PB, SL(W), PA(W)).

3.1 Matrices

data_seabirds.no_HJ <- subset(data_seabirds, host_species != "HJ")

PA.matrix.motu.no_HJ <- dcast(data_seabirds.no_HJ, Extraction_ID ~ final_id, function(x) if(length(x)>=1) 1 else 0, value.var = "final_id")
PA.matrix.motu.no_HJ2 <- PA.matrix.motu.no_HJ %>% remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="Extraction_ID")

factors.no_HJ <- data_seabirds.no_HJ %>% dplyr::select(Extraction_ID, host_species, host_season, season) %>% distinct(Extraction_ID, .keep_all = TRUE)
factors.no_HJ[] <- lapply(factors.no_HJ[colnames(factors.no_HJ)], as.factor)

factors.no_HJ.ord <- factors.no_HJ[order(factors.no_HJ$Extraction_ID),] %>% remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="Extraction_ID")

3.2 Frequency of Ocurrence (%)

sample.matrix.motu.no_HJ.long <- gather(PA.matrix.motu.no_HJ, Species, Presence, "Acanthuridae":"Trichiuridae", factor_key=TRUE)
sample.matrix.motu.no_HJ.long <- merge(sample.matrix.motu.no_HJ.long, factors.no_HJ)

host_season.matrix.motu.long.good <- ddply(.data = sample.matrix.motu.no_HJ.long, .var = c("host_season", "host_species", "Species"), .fun = summarise,
    n = length(Presence),
    present = sum(Presence %in% c("1")),
    prop = present / n * 100
)

host_season.matrix.motu.wide.good <- host_season.matrix.motu.long.good %>%
  subset(select=c("host_season", "n", "Species", "prop"))%>%
  spread(Species, prop)
host_season.matrix.motu.wide.good <- host_season.matrix.motu.wide.good %>% remove_rownames %>% column_to_rownames(var="host_season")

3.5 Network analysis using FI

host_season.net.matrix <- host_season.matrix.motu.long.good[,c(1,3,5)] %>% filter(present > 0) %>% dplyr::rename(higher = host_season, lower = Species, freq = present)
host_season.net.matrix$webID = "caboverde"
host_season.net.matrix <- host_season.net.matrix[, c(1, 2, 4, 3)]

seq.high <- as.data.frame(host_season.net.matrix$higher)%>% dplyr::rename(seq.high = "host_season.net.matrix$higher") %>% distinct(seq.high)
seq.low <- as.data.frame(host_season.net.matrix$lower)%>% dplyr::rename(seq.low = "host_season.net.matrix$lower") %>% distinct(seq.low)

host_season.network <- frame2webs(data.frame(host_season.net.matrix),type.out="list")

3.5.5 Comparisons of Module based metrics with Null model

Null model cz-values:

nulls_cvalues_HL <- sapply(nulls, function(x) czvalues(metaComputeModules(x))$c)
quantile(nulls_cvalues_HL, 0.95)
##  95% 
## 0.73
nulls_zvalues_HL <- sapply(nulls, function(x) czvalues(metaComputeModules(x))$z)
nulls_zvalues_HL[is.na(nulls_zvalues_HL)] <- 0
quantile(nulls_zvalues_HL, 0.95)
##       95% 
## 0.7071068
nulls_cvalues_LL <- sapply(nulls, function(x) czvalues(metaComputeModules(x), level = "lower")$c)
quantile(nulls_cvalues_LL, 0.95)
##  95% 
## 0.75
nulls_zvalues_LL <- sapply(nulls, function(x) czvalues(metaComputeModules(x), level = "lower")$z)
nulls_zvalues_LL[is.na(nulls_zvalues_LL)] <- 0
quantile(nulls_zvalues_LL, 0.95)
##      95% 
## 1.502938

Plots

  • Higher level
HL_czplot <- ggplot(host_season.HL.cz, aes(x=c, y=z)) +
  xlim(0, 1) +
  ylim(-1, 1) +
  geom_point(size = 2) + 
  geom_vline(xintercept = quantile(nulls_cvalues_HL, 0.95), linetype="dashed", color = "grey") + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = quantile(nulls_zvalues_HL, 0.95), linetype="dashed", color = "grey") +
  geom_text_repel(data=subset(host_season.HL.cz, c > quantile(nulls_cvalues_HL, 0.95) | z > quantile(nulls_zvalues_HL, 0.95)), aes(label = row.names(subset(host_season.HL.cz, c > quantile(nulls_cvalues_HL, 0.95) | z > quantile(nulls_zvalues_HL, 0.95)))))

HL_czplot

  • Lower level

3.6 Pianka niche overlap between populations

The Pianka overlap index was calculated, and the significance of each overlap was calculated over a simulated matrix using ecosimR. HJ was excluded from this analysis due to its low sample size.

overlap.host_season.motu.data <- host_season.matrix.motu.wide.good[-1]
overlap.host_season.motu.data2 <- as.data.frame(t(overlap.host_season.motu.data))

pianka.host_season.motu <- niche.overlap(overlap.host_season.motu.data2, method = "pianka")
pianka.host_season.motu
